comment.narrative:
1.1. No regulations in support of RES Law;
1.2. RES Law includes a number of provisions to facilitate investment in grid-connected RE projects, but they are not operationalized;
1.3. Weak capacity of the staff members from relevant central and local government institutions in developing and coordinating SHP projects;
2.1. Lack of instruction manuals on SHP project development;
2.2. Lack of local manufacturers capable of providing turn-key integrated RES solution and O&M services; 
2.3. No vocational training on SHP and lack of facilities to train technicians on SHP;
3.1. Lack of access to SHP for productive uses and livelihoods;
3.2. Lack of feasibility studies;
3.3. No integrated district development plan;
3.4. Lack of SHP projects in the pipe-line;
3.5. No PPAs signed for purchase of power from pilot SHPs;
3.6. Lack of replication and scaling up of EE and RES;
3.7. Lack of control over GHG emissions;
3.8. Lack of government investment in new SHP plants.
